04139nam a22005775i 9780774825108DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748251087 a10.59962/97807748251082doi  a(DE-B1597)661948  a(OCoLC)1058942904  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE78.C2 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a305.897/0712231 aAltamirano-Jiménez, Isabel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIndigenous Encounters with Neoliberalism :bPlace, Women, and the Environment in Canada and Mexico /cIsabel Altamirano-Jiménez. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (284 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWomen and Indigenous Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Political Economy of Indigeneity Articulation -- tIndigeneity, Nature, and Neoliberalism -- tNunavut -- tThe Nisga’a “Common Bowl,” Gender, and Property Rights -- tThe Zapatista Movement -- tIndigeneity, Land, and Gender in Oaxaca -- tConclusion -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe recognition of Indigenous rights and the management of land and resources have always been fraught with complex power relations and conflicting expressions of identity. In Indigenous Encounters with Neoliberalism, Isabel Altamirano-Jiménez explores how this issue is playing out in two countries very differently marked by neoliberalism's local expressions – Canada and Mexico. Weaving together four distinct case studies, two from each country, Altamirano-Jiménez presents insights from Indigenous feminism, critical geography, political economy, and postcolonial studies. These specific examples highlight Indigenous people's responses to neoliberalism, reflecting the tensions that result from how Indigenous identity, gender, and the environment have been connected. Indigenous women's perspectives are particularly illuminating as they articulate diverse aspirations and concerns within a wider political framework. What emerges is a theoretical and empirical discussion of how indigeneity as an act of articulation is embedded in tensions between local needs and global wants. This study attempts to uncover the complexities of materializing neoliberalism and the fluidity of indigeneity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInuitzNunavutvCase studies. 0aNeoliberalismzCanada. 0aNiska IndiansvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482510840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774825108423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774825108/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles